{
  "texts": [
    "Students who participated in this study received a 3% extra credit for this course and an additional 20$ for their participation.",
    "This amount was supported by a grant from the National Natural Science Foundation of China (Grants No. 31571141 and No. 31628010)",
    "Radical embodied cognitive science (RECS) proposes a contrary view to representationalists' assumptions in the cognitive sciences (e.g.,Fodor and Pylyshyn 1988).",
    "While mental representations are thought to be mental processes that allow for the encoding of aspects of an external world, RECS traces cognition not to internal symbol processing but to organism-environment coupling.",
    "Drawing on key ideas from ecological psychology(Gibson 1979) that trace direct perception to an organism's activity, RECS assigns cognition to an organism's actions rather than stable mental representations."
  ]
}